A rocky embankment separates the river fence from the park and among the rocks is a warren of Ground Squirrel tunnels.  When I approached, I was startled by a loud motherly screech and a flurry of tiny fuzz balls disappeared into those holes.  I settled down to watch... and after only a few moments, one tiny furry head after another began to peek out at the intruder.
Cool and overcast, it was a great day for worms.  Or worm eaters.  Even the Starlings got into the hunt.

With the northern bank of the stream temporarily blocked for concrete repair, the local Killdeer have less cover from wandering intruders.  When I stumbled by, this attractive bird hopped up and began to do an elaborate fan dance.  I was momentarily mesmerized, until I realized it had perceived me as a threat (to possible nestlings)  and I quickly, and quietly, egressed.
I was heading back to my car when a noisy group of parrots arrived.  I go close enough for a couple shots a pair of Lilac-crowned Parrots grooming.

Made a short trip to the river at Bette Davis to check on the progress of the concrete river repair. The work is still paused, due to nesting birds in the river.  (Yes... how great is that!)  As I walked along the north bank, I heard the high-pitched alarm cries of a pair of Killdeer and spotted one adult which began a "nest distraction" display nearby. I quietly backed off, but kept an eye on the area from a distance, and was treated to the sight of two (or possibly three) fledgling Killdeer, as they popped up to see what the fuss was about. The thing that I noticed, which surprised me a bit, was that the tiny birds did not huddle together after the parent's alarm, but apparently headed off in separate directions. I only noticed them, singly, as they emerged from behind rocks and under brush. Two for sure, possibly more. The tiny fledgling shown must have been standing in the duckweed, hidden behind that muddy embankment, as his legs seem to be covered with it.  Juveniles have just a single chest band.

This is the first I have seen this year, although I have looked regularly from mid-May on. There are many potential host webs, so far all labyrinth spiders at this location.

I was surprised to find such a mature individual so early in the season. She is approximately 3 mm from chelicerae to spinnerets, and around 10 mm when legs are taken into account. Perhaps this individual spent the last eight months in dormancy as a near adult rather than as a spiderling.

It will be interesting to see if the labyrinth spider host survives since it is no larger than this dewdrop spider and, presumably, no match for it should she choose to prey on it.

I am adding this a bit late to fill in my Sunday report at Rio de Los Angeles.   This was the first of three American Kestrels that I saw that morning.  I heard this one making repeated loud cries from a wire just inside the NW corner of the park.  Sounded to me like juvenile begging cries.  Soon thereafter a male Kestrel landed on the wire nearby and was followed by a female which flew past and landed on a light stanchion on the north side of the baseball diamond.  When the two adults left and flew west across the railroad tracks, this bird remained on the wire until after I left.
Second photo shows it with prey which it came back with about 5-10 minutes after I first photographed it

Poor guys fell out of their nest and seemed to be suffering heat exhaustion in the 110° weather. I was able to cool them down with cold water on their feet, but unfortunately 2 of them ended up dying and a third went missing. I attempted to place the remaining one back in the nest when it cooled down outside, but it kept jumping out of the nest so I ended up leaving it in the box placed near the nest. Mama bird was nearby so hopefully she’ll feed it :(

FLEDGLING WESTERN BLUEBIRD.
This cute little bird had me fooled for a moment; but I have been following a gorgeous pair of Western Bluebirds in this section of the park for months, and it finally dawned on me that this might be the result of their collaboration.  Don't know if it is male or female, but its distinctive coloring is spectacular!  The second photo is mom, perched high at the top of the next tree over, keeping a parental eye on junior.

FLEDGLING WITH ADULT BLACK PHOEBE.
What is missing in the variety of birds at this time of year, is compensated for by some neat views of fledglings.  The bird on the right (with rufous edges on its wing feathers) is a recently fledged Black Phoebe.  One of its parents is on the left.  I included an additional photo of each.

Was visually following this Yellow Warbler when it landed on an open branch next to a much larger bird.  To my surprise, the adult warbler began feeding the large fledgling Brown-headed Cowbird.  A very graphic illustration of the Cowbird's practice of laying its eggs in the nests of other birds.  Even much smaller birds, like this Yellow Warbler.  Unfortunately, the warbler's own young tend not to survive.

The larger bird in this photo is a fledgling Brown-headed Cowbird, being fed by a tiny Yellow Warbler after being hatched in the warbler's nest.  The Cowbirds have a parasitic practice of lying their eggs in the nests of other birds.  As a result, the young of the unsuspecting host bird tend not to survive.  I suspect in this case, it also puts a great deal of stress on the adult birds, as they attempt to feed this huge chick.

SUNNING BEHAVIOR - MALE AMERICAN ROBIN.
A pair of American Robins lives in the area near the bathrooms, likely nesting in the trees.  Today, I got lucky and witnessed the male performing what is known as "sunning".  It reminded me, at first, of the protective displays used by other species to divert predators from their nests.  Since Robins nest in trees, this seemed unlikely.  A bit of research led me to an activity called "sunning".  Since the day was not particularly cool, I believe the most likely motivation in this instance might be feather conditioning, as well as helping to dislodge parasites.  Fascinating to watch.

I have been following a pair of American Robins for months and on the lookout for any fledglings.  Today I finally succeeded in photographing what appears to be a juvenile Robin feeding under a Walnut tree near an adult female.  An adult male was under another tree not far off.  The juvenile (in the third photo) shows some residual white spotting on the back and white areas remaining on the breast.
I could easily be wrong in the ID but this is for the tubey one. 400x magnification

400x magnification, found in some macroscopic cyanobacteria  that was growing in still water accumulating in the middle of an intersection. 

A red eye can be seen, I believe there are two red eyes (many of the nearby rotifers in this sample had them) however the rotifer was on its side obscuring one.  The mastax can be seen in motion in the second video.

The gifs remove the red coloration from the eye and blur the video for some reason, so I attached two still photos as well that captured the original color and detail that I saw, in addition to a tube like structure above the head.

I believe this is Philodina roseola.
This is likely a juvenile due to the brown edging on the flight feathers.
Most likely a female Brown-headed Cowbird.

for the smaller left rotifer. 400x magnification. these rotifers were found in a bubbly macroscopic nostoc cyanobacteria found in some sitting water pooling in the middle of the street.

two red eye dots on this smaller rotifer were seen in the larger one as well, leading me to believe they are both genus Philodina, perhaps the common rotifer.

In the macroscopic photo, this cyanobacteria is the green flakey algae like material with bubbly structures in it.

For months, I was seeing white pelicans at the lake in the Sepulveda Basin Wildlife Reserve. There numbers dwindled from a few dozen to a handful, then 3, finally one, and then none. My understanding is they migrate elsewhere to lay their eggs. After weeks of not seeing any, I was surprised on this day to see one fly over the lake twice. My view was clearer than my photos. The strikingly white feathers with the black trim & the pelican’s bill definitely distinguished it from the gulls & egrets.
